<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	Guided Lecture Notes worksheet: "Slope Fields and Qualitative Analysis"
	Book sections (Exploring Differential Equations, geoff-cox/debookrs):
		c6-qm/sec-slope-fields.ptx
		c6-qm/sec-autonomous-equations.ptx
		c6-qm/sec-equilibrium-solutions.ptx
		c6-qm/sec-classifying-equilibrium-solutions.ptx
		c6-qm/sec-logistical-models.ptx
		c6-qm/sec-parameter-analysis.ptx
	Old deck: source/notes/latex/ folder "08 slope-fields"
	(structured_notes_slope_fields.tex plus figs/).
	Previous worksheet: ws-integrating-factors.ptx; next: ws-eulers-method.

	Per the sourcing rules, every equation here is fresh: concepts mirror
	the book, but none of the example equations appear in it (nor in the
	old deck or the earlier worksheets). Per the instructor overrides in
	CLAUDE.md section 4: no interactive content (print-first, so all
	slope-field work is hand-constructed: slope tables, student-drawn
	grids, text phase lines), and the whole topic stays on this one
	worksheet.

	FIGURES: dense computer-drawn slope fields would enrich pages 1-2 but
	are not required by any exercise. Placeholder locations are marked
	with TODO(geoff) comments naming candidate source images from the old
	deck's figs/ directory (repo-internal, read-only). Listed under the
	PR's Open questions.

	Worksheet conventions: checklists/worksheet-conventions.md (see
	CLAUDE.md section 4 for this repo's parameters). In brief:
	  * Student/instructor split via component="stu" / component="key",
	    mirrored in structure; answers never live inside <fillin>.
	  * Worked problems: paired <exercise component="stu" workspace="Xin">
	    and <exercise component="key"> (statement + solution).
	  * True/False checks: one <exercise> + <solution component="key">.
	  * <page> = vertical print space, not topics; headings are
	    <p><term>...</term></p>; display math uses <md> (<me>/<men> are
	    prohibited here).
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-slope-fields" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Slope Fields and Qualitative Analysis</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li><p><term>Evaluate</term> the slope generator <m>f(t,y)</m> at a point and sketch a small slope field by hand.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Recognize</term> autonomous equations and the striped pattern of their slope fields.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Find</term> equilibrium solutions by solving <m>f(y) = 0</m>.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Construct</term> a phase line and classify each equilibrium as a sink, source, or node&#8212;by sign analysis and by the <m>f'(c)</m> test.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Predict</term> the long-term behavior of solutions without solving the equation, including a harvested logistic population.</p></li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 1 : The slope generator; sketching a field by hand              -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Reading behavior without solving.</term></p>

		<p>
			Every technique so far produced a formula for <m>y</m>. This worksheet
			flips the question: what can an equation <m>y' = f(t,y)</m> tell us
			about its solutions <em>directly</em>, with no integration at all? The
			right side is a <em>slope generator</em>: feed it any point
			<m>(t,y)</m> and it returns the slope a solution must have there.
			Plotting a short segment with that slope at many points produces a
			<term>slope field</term>&#8212;a navigational chart every solution
			must obey.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						A slope field does not display one particular solution; it
						visualizes the entire <fillin characters="8"/> of solutions at
						once. From any starting point, a solution curve threads through
						the field by following the <fillin characters="8"/> segments.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						A slope field does not display one particular solution; it
						visualizes the entire <m>\underline{\textbf{family}}</m> of
						solutions at once. From any starting point, a solution curve
						threads through the field by following the
						<m>\underline{\textbf{slope}}</m> segments.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-tf-solve">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>To sketch a slope field for <m>y' = f(t,y)</m>, you must first solve the differential equation.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False&#8212;that is the whole point. The slope generator
					<m>f(t,y)</m> is read straight off the equation, so the field
					costs only arithmetic. Slope fields exist precisely for the many
					equations we <em>cannot</em> solve in closed form.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-table" component="stu" workspace="2.8in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the differential equation
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = t^2 - y. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Complete the table of slopes.
					(b) On your own <m>(t,y)</m> axes, sketch the nine slope segments
					to form a miniature slope field.
					(c) What slope does a solution through <m>(2, 1)</m> have there?
				</p>
				<tabular halign="center">
					<col right="minor"/>
					<row bottom="minor">
						<cell><m>f(t,y) = t^2 - y</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=-1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=0</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=1</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=1</m></cell>
						<cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=0</m></cell>
						<cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=-1</m></cell>
						<cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-table" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the differential equation
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = t^2 - y. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Complete the table of slopes.
					(b) On your own <m>(t,y)</m> axes, sketch the nine slope segments
					to form a miniature slope field.
					(c) What slope does a solution through <m>(2, 1)</m> have there?
				</p>
				<tabular halign="center">
					<col right="minor"/>
					<row bottom="minor">
						<cell><m>f(t,y) = t^2 - y</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=-1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=0</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=1</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=1</m></cell>
						<cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=0</m></cell>
						<cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=-1</m></cell>
						<cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Substituting each pair into <m>f(t,y) = t^2 - y</m>:
				</p>
				<tabular halign="center">
					<col right="minor"/>
					<row bottom="minor">
						<cell><m>f(t,y)</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=-1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=0</m></cell>
						<cell><m>t=1</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>0</m></cell><cell><m>-1</m></cell><cell><m>0</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=0</m></cell>
						<cell><m>1</m></cell><cell><m>0</m></cell><cell><m>1</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>y=-1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>2</m></cell><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell><m>2</m></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
				<p>
					(b) At each grid point, draw a short segment with the tabulated
					slope&#8212;e.g. flat at <m>(-1,1)</m>, falling at <m>(0,1)</m>,
					steep (slope <m>2</m>) at <m>(\pm 1,-1)</m>. Notice the pattern is
					<em>not</em> constant along horizontal rows: the slope depends on
					<m>t</m> as well as <m>y</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) <m>f(2,1) = 4 - 1 = 3</m>. Any solution passing through
					<m>(2,1)</m> leaves that point with slope <m>3</m>&#8212;no
					solving required.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<!-- TODO(geoff): optional enrichment figure here: a dense
		     computer-generated slope field for dy/dt = t^2 - y so students can
		     compare their 3x3 hand sketch to the full picture. Candidate
		     source assets from the old deck (read-only, would need to be
		     re-exported into source/notes/assets/): 08 slope-fields
		     figs/DE_C_fine.eps or regenerate via figs/slope_fields.m.
		     No exercise depends on it. -->
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 2 : Autonomous equations and equilibrium solutions              -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Autonomous equations: stripes and standstills.</term></p>

		<p>
			When the slope generator has no explicit <m>t</m> in it&#8212;<m>y' = f(y)</m>&#8212;the
			equation is <term>autonomous</term> (<q>self-governing</q>): how fast
			<m>y</m> changes depends only on the current value of <m>y</m>, not on
			the clock. In the slope field this shows up as horizontal
			<em>stripes</em>: slide left or right and the segments never change.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						An equation <m>y' = f(y)</m> is called <fillin characters="10"/>
						because its rate of change depends only on the current state,
						not on <fillin characters="4"/>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						An equation <m>y' = f(y)</m> is called
						<m>\underline{\textbf{autonomous}}</m> because its rate of change
						depends only on the current state, not on
						<m>\underline{\textbf{time}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						A constant solution <m>y(t) = c</m> where the system stops
						changing is called an <fillin characters="11"/> solution; to find
						them all, set <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> equal to <fillin characters="4"/>
						and solve for <m>y</m>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						A constant solution <m>y(t) = c</m> where the system stops
						changing is called an <m>\underline{\textbf{equilibrium}}</m>
						solution; to find them all, set <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> equal to
						<m>\underline{\textbf{zero}}</m> and solve for <m>y</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-tf-stripes">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>For an autonomous equation, the slope-field segments at <m>(1, 2)</m> and <m>(5, 2)</m> have the same slope.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					True. Both points have <m>y = 2</m>, and an autonomous slope
					generator <m>f(y)</m> only looks at <m>y</m>: the slope is
					<m>f(2)</m> at both. That is exactly why autonomous fields look
					striped&#8212;and why the whole field can be compressed into a
					single vertical phase line.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-equilibria" component="stu" workspace="2.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the autonomous equation
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = y^2 - 9. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Find all equilibrium solutions.
					(b) The equilibria split the <m>y</m>-axis into three regions; use
					a test point in each to decide where solutions rise and where they
					fall.
					(c) Describe what the slope field looks like along the lines
					<m>y = 3</m> and <m>y = -3</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-equilibria" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the autonomous equation
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = y^2 - 9. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Find all equilibrium solutions.
					(b) The equilibria split the <m>y</m>-axis into three regions; use
					a test point in each to decide where solutions rise and where they
					fall.
					(c) Describe what the slope field looks like along the lines
					<m>y = 3</m> and <m>y = -3</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Set <m>y = c</m> constant, so <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = 0</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> 0 = c^2 - 9 = (c-3)(c+3) \quad\Rightarrow\quad c = \pm 3, </mrow>
					</md>
					giving the equilibrium solutions <m>y(t) = 3</m> and
					<m>y(t) = -3</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Testing <m>f(y) = y^2 - 9</m> in each region:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li><p><m>y &gt; 3</m>: <m>f(4) = 7 &gt; 0</m>, solutions <em>rise</em>;</p></li>
						<li><p><m>-3 &lt; y &lt; 3</m>: <m>f(0) = -9 &lt; 0</m>, solutions <em>fall</em>;</p></li>
						<li><p><m>y &lt; -3</m>: <m>f(-4) = 7 &gt; 0</m>, solutions <em>rise</em>.</p></li>
					</ul>
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Along <m>y = \pm 3</m> every segment is perfectly
					<em>horizontal</em>&#8212;two flat stripes running across the whole
					field. A solution that starts on one of those lines stays on it
					forever.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 3 : Phase lines; classifying equilibria (signs and f'(c))       -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>The phase line: a slope field squeezed to one axis.</term></p>

		<p>
			For an autonomous equation, every column of the striped slope field
			carries the same information, so we compress the whole picture onto a
			single vertical <m>y</m>-axis: dots at the equilibria, an upward arrow
			wherever <m>f(y) &gt; 0</m>, a downward arrow wherever
			<m>f(y) &lt; 0</m>. This <term>phase line</term> tells the long-term
			story of every solution at a glance.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						An equilibrium that attracts solutions from both sides is
						<term>stable</term>, also called a <fillin characters="6"/>; one
						that repels on both sides is <term>unstable</term>, also called a
						<fillin characters="7"/>; one that attracts on one side and repels
						on the other is <term>semi-stable</term>, also called a
						<fillin characters="5"/>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						An equilibrium that attracts solutions from both sides is
						<term>stable</term>, also called a
						<m>\underline{\textbf{sink}}</m>; one that repels on both sides is
						<term>unstable</term>, also called a
						<m>\underline{\textbf{source}}</m>; one that attracts on one side
						and repels on the other is <term>semi-stable</term>, also called a
						<m>\underline{\textbf{node}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-phaseline" component="stu" workspace="2.2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Return to <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = y^2 - 9</m> from the previous page.
					(a) Draw its phase line: mark the equilibria and add the up/down
					arrows from your sign analysis.
					(b) Classify each equilibrium as a sink, source, or node.
					(c) A solution starts at <m>y(0) = 0</m>. What is
					<m>\lim_{t\to\infty} y(t)</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-phaseline" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Return to <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = y^2 - 9</m> from the previous page.
					(a) Draw its phase line: mark the equilibria and add the up/down
					arrows from your sign analysis.
					(b) Classify each equilibrium as a sink, source, or node.
					(c) A solution starts at <m>y(0) = 0</m>. What is
					<m>\lim_{t\to\infty} y(t)</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) The phase line, drawn vertically (arrows show the sign of
					<m>f</m>): up above <m>3</m>, down between <m>-3</m> and <m>3</m>,
					up below <m>-3</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> \begin{array}{ccl} \uparrow &amp; &amp; f&gt;0 \\ \bullet &amp; y=3 &amp; \\ \downarrow &amp; &amp; f&lt;0 \\ \bullet &amp; y=-3 &amp; \\ \uparrow &amp; &amp; f&gt;0 \end{array} </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) At <m>y = -3</m>, arrows point toward the dot from both sides
					(up from below, down from above): a <term>sink</term> (stable). At
					<m>y = 3</m>, arrows point away on both sides: a
					<term>source</term> (unstable).
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Starting at <m>y(0) = 0</m>, between the equilibria, the arrow
					is downward, so the solution decreases and levels off at the sink:
					<m>\lim_{t\to\infty} y(t) = -3</m>. We predicted the destiny of the
					solution without ever solving the equation.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p>
			<term>A calculus shortcut.</term> The sign of <m>f'(c)</m> at an
			equilibrium <m>c</m> classifies it instantly: <m>f'(c) &lt; 0</m> means
			sink, <m>f'(c) &gt; 0</m> means source, and <m>f'(c) = 0</m> means the
			test is inconclusive&#8212;fall back on the phase line.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-node" component="stu" workspace="2.8in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Now analyze
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = y\,(y - 2)^2. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Find the equilibria.
					(b) Try the <m>f'(c)</m> test at each; where it is inconclusive,
					build the phase line instead.
					(c) Classify each equilibrium.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-node" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Now analyze
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = y\,(y - 2)^2. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Find the equilibria.
					(b) Try the <m>f'(c)</m> test at each; where it is inconclusive,
					build the phase line instead.
					(c) Classify each equilibrium.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) <m>f(y) = y(y-2)^2 = 0</m> at <m>y = 0</m> and <m>y = 2</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) By the product rule,
					<m>f'(y) = (y-2)^2 + 2y(y-2) = (y-2)(3y-2)</m>. Then
					<m>f'(0) = (-2)(-2) = 4 &gt; 0</m>: <m>y=0</m> is a
					<term>source</term>. But <m>f'(2) = 0</m>&#8212;inconclusive, so
					check signs around <m>y = 2</m>: <m>f(1) = (1)(1) = 1 &gt; 0</m>
					(rising below) and <m>f(3) = (3)(1) = 3 &gt; 0</m> (rising above).
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Solutions climb <em>toward</em> <m>y=2</m> from below but climb
					<em>away</em> from it above: <m>y = 2</m> is a <term>node</term>
					(semi-stable). The squared factor is the tell-tale: <m>f</m>
					touches zero at <m>y=2</m> without changing sign, so the arrows on
					both sides point the same way.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-tf-fprime">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>If <m>f'(c) = 0</m> at an equilibrium <m>c</m>, then <m>c</m> must be semi-stable.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False. <m>f'(c) = 0</m> only means the shortcut is
					<em>inconclusive</em>. For <m>y' = y^3</m>, <m>f'(0) = 0</m> yet
					<m>y=0</m> is a source (negative below, positive above); for
					<m>y' = -y^3</m> it is a sink. Only the phase line settles it.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 4 : Qualitative payoff: a harvested logistic population         -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>The payoff: a harvested population, no solving required.</term></p>

		<p>
			In the separation-of-variables worksheet, extracting the logistic
			solution formula took real work. Qualitative analysis gets the story
			for free&#8212;and it keeps working when we modify the model in ways
			that make the formula ugly.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-logistic" component="stu" workspace="2.4in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A fish population (in hundreds) obeys the logistic equation
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dP}{dt} = 0.2\,P\left(1 - \frac{P}{500}\right). </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Find and classify the equilibria.
					(b) Predict <m>\lim_{t\to\infty} P(t)</m> if <m>P(0) = 50</m>, and
					if <m>P(0) = 800</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-logistic" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A fish population (in hundreds) obeys the logistic equation
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dP}{dt} = 0.2\,P\left(1 - \frac{P}{500}\right). </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Find and classify the equilibria.
					(b) Predict <m>\lim_{t\to\infty} P(t)</m> if <m>P(0) = 50</m>, and
					if <m>P(0) = 800</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) <m>f(P) = 0.2P(1 - P/500) = 0</m> at <m>P = 0</m> and
					<m>P = 500</m> (the carrying capacity). Signs: <m>f(100) &gt; 0</m>
					(rising between) and <m>f(600) &lt; 0</m> (falling above), so
					<m>P = 0</m> is a <term>source</term> and <m>P = 500</m> is a
					<term>sink</term>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) From <m>P(0) = 50</m> the solution rises toward the sink:
					<m>P \to 500</m>. From <m>P(0) = 800</m> it falls toward the same
					sink: <m>P \to 500</m>. Either way the population settles at
					carrying capacity&#8212;the entire logistic story, read off a phase
					line in three lines of arithmetic.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-harvest" component="stu" workspace="3.0in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Now suppose the fishery harvests at a constant rate <m>h</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dP}{dt} = 0.2\,P\left(1 - \frac{P}{500}\right) - h. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) For <m>h = 9</m>, find the equilibria and classify each.
					(b) Show that the equilibria are <m>P = 250 \pm 50\sqrt{25 - h}</m>
					in general, and find the critical harvesting rate beyond which
					<em>no</em> equilibrium exists.
					(c) What happens to the population when <m>h</m> exceeds that
					critical rate?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-sf-ex-harvest" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Now suppose the fishery harvests at a constant rate <m>h</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dP}{dt} = 0.2\,P\left(1 - \frac{P}{500}\right) - h. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) For <m>h = 9</m>, find the equilibria and classify each.
					(b) Show that the equilibria are <m>P = 250 \pm 50\sqrt{25 - h}</m>
					in general, and find the critical harvesting rate beyond which
					<em>no</em> equilibrium exists.
					(c) What happens to the population when <m>h</m> exceeds that
					critical rate?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Setting <m>f(P) = 0.2P - 0.0004P^2 - 9 = 0</m> and multiplying
					by <m>-2500</m>: <m>P^2 - 500P + 22500 = 0</m>, so
					<m>P = 50</m> or <m>P = 450</m>. The parabola <m>f(P)</m> opens
					downward, so <m>f &lt; 0</m> below <m>50</m>, <m>f &gt; 0</m>
					between, <m>f &lt; 0</m> above <m>450</m>: <m>P = 50</m> is a
					<term>source</term> and <m>P = 450</m> a <term>sink</term>. (New
					danger compared with <m>h=0</m>: a stock that ever dips below
					<m>50</m> is driven to collapse.)
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) In general <m>0.0004P^2 - 0.2P + h = 0</m> gives
					<md>
						<mrow> P = \frac{0.2 \pm \sqrt{0.04 - 0.0016h}}{0.0008} = 250 \pm 50\sqrt{25 - h}. </mrow>
					</md>
					Real equilibria require <m>25 - h \ge 0</m>, so the critical rate is
					<m>h = 25</m>. As <m>h</m> grows toward <m>25</m>, the source and
					the sink slide toward each other and at <m>h = 25</m> they collide
					and annihilate&#8212;a bifurcation.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) For <m>h &gt; 25</m> there are no equilibria and
					<m>f(P) &lt; 0</m> for every <m>P</m>: the phase line points down
					everywhere, so <m>P(t)</m> decreases no matter how large it
					starts. On the physically meaningful domain <m>P \ge 0</m>, the
					population is therefore driven down to <m>P = 0</m>&#8212;extinction&#8212;and
					the model stops applying there (the raw equation would happily
					continue into negative <m>P</m>, which means nothing for a
					fishery). The model draws a hard sustainability line at harvesting
					<m>25</m>&#8212;a conclusion we reached without solving anything.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<title>Looking ahead</title>
			<p>
				Qualitative analysis tells us the <em>shape</em> of the story:
				where solutions settle, where they flee, where a model breaks. What
				it does not give is numbers&#8212;the population <em>at year
				three</em>, say. The next worksheet builds <em>Euler's method</em>,
				which turns the same slope generator into a step-by-step numerical
				approximation of a solution.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>
</worksheet>
